@page "/guide"
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.Web
@using Microsoft.JSInterop
@inject IJSRuntime JSRuntime

<PageTitle>Workflow Diagram Annotations Guide</PageTitle>

<div class="annotations-guide">
    <h1 class="mb-4">Workflow Diagram Annotations Guide</h1>

    <div class="alert alert-light border mb-4">
        <p class="mb-0">
            <strong>In brief:</strong> Add special markers (attributes) to your Temporal workflow code so this dashboard can draw a diagram of the workflow automatically. 
            You mark the workflow itself, each step, and how steps connect. No separate diagram file is needed.
        </p>
    </div>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>
            Workflows in this dashboard are discovered from .NET assemblies. To generate a diagram, the workflow class and its steps are decorated with attributes 
            from <code>TemporalDashboard.WorkflowDiagramming.Attributes</code>. The dashboard reads these at runtime and produces a Mermaid flowchart.
        </p>
        <div class="alert alert-info">
            <strong>For business users:</strong> Think of attributes as labels you attach to the workflow and to each step. 
            The labels describe the step name, the type (e.g. “decision” or “approval”), and which step comes next. The dashboard uses that to draw the flow.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Getting Started</h2>
        <p>Add these namespaces at the top of your workflow file:</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">using Temporalio.Workflows;
using TemporalDashboard.WorkflowDiagramming.Attributes;</code></pre>
        <p class="mt-3">Then apply attributes to the workflow class and to the method that runs the workflow (the <em>run</em> method).</p>
        <div class="alert alert-warning">
            <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark me-2">Technical</span>
            The run method must be the one marked with <code>[WorkflowRun]</code> from Temporal. The diagram start node is attached to that method via <code>[WorkflowStart]</code>.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>1. Mark the Workflow and Its Start</h2>
        <p>On the workflow class, use <code>[Workflow]</code> (Temporal) and <code>[WorkflowDiagram]</code>. On the run method, use <code>[WorkflowRun]</code> and <code>[WorkflowStart]</code>.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[Workflow]
[WorkflowDiagram(DisplayName = "Customer Onboarding", Direction = "TD")]
public class CustomerOnboardingWorkflow
{
    [WorkflowRun]
    [WorkflowStart("Begin Onboarding")]
    public async Task&lt;Result&gt; RunAsync(Request request) => await ExecuteAsync(request);
}</code></pre>
        <ul class="mt-2">
            <li><strong>DisplayName</strong> — Shown in the UI; use a business-friendly name.</li>
            <li><strong>Direction</strong> — <code>TD</code> (top-down), <code>LR</code> (left-right), <code>TB</code>, <code>BT</code>.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>2. Mark Each Step</h2>
        <p>Use <code>[WorkflowStep]</code> on methods (or a dedicated “steps” method) with a unique <strong>id</strong>, a <strong>label</strong>, and an <strong>order</strong> number.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[WorkflowStep("validate", "Validate Request", 1)]
private async Task ValidateRequest() { }

[WorkflowStep("process", "Process Data", 2)]
private async Task ProcessData() { }

[WorkflowStep("notify", "Send Notification", 3, IsAiPowered = true)]
private async Task NotifyWithAI() { }</code></pre>
        <div class="alert alert-secondary">
            <strong>Technical:</strong> <code>WorkflowStep(id, label, order)</code>. Optional: <code>StepType</code> (Activity, Decision, HumanApproval, Start, End), <code>Description</code>, <code>IsAiPowered</code>, <code>IsSuccess</code>, <code>IsFailure</code>.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>3. Connect Steps with Transitions</h2>
        <p>Use <code>[WorkflowTransition(fromId, toId)]</code> to define arrows between steps. You can put several on one method. The start node ID is <code>"Start"</code> (capital S).</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[WorkflowTransition("Start", "validate")]
[WorkflowTransition("validate", "process")]
[WorkflowTransition("process", "notify")]
[WorkflowTransition("notify", "end")]
public void Transitions() { }</code></pre>
        <div class="alert alert-info">
            <strong>For business users:</strong> Each transition is “from this step, the flow can go to that step.” Labels are optional (e.g. “Yes” / “No” on branches).
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>4. Decisions and Branches</h2>
        <p>For a decision point, use <code>[WorkflowDecision]</code> on the decision step. Use <code>[WorkflowBranch]</code> (not <code>WorkflowTransition</code>) for each outcome.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[WorkflowDecision("check", "Is Eligible?", 2)]
private async Task&lt;bool&gt; CheckEligibility() => true;

[WorkflowBranch("check", "Yes", "process")]
[WorkflowBranch("check", "No", "rejected", IsFailurePath = true)]
public void DecisionBranches() { }</code></pre>
        <div class="alert alert-warning">
            <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark me-2">Technical</span>
            Do not use <code>[WorkflowTransition]</code> from a decision node; use only <code>[WorkflowBranch]</code> so the diagram renders the decision correctly.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>5. Human Approval and End Steps</h2>
        <p>Use <code>[WorkflowHumanApproval]</code> for steps that require a person, and <code>[WorkflowEnd]</code> for success/failure outcomes.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[WorkflowHumanApproval("approval", "Manager Approval", 4,
    Description = "Requires manager sign-off",
    Timeout = "24 hours",
    ApproverRole = "Line Manager")]
private async Task RequestApproval() { }

[WorkflowEnd("approved", "Approved", true)]
private void Approved() { }

[WorkflowEnd("rejected", "Rejected", false)]
private void Rejected() { }</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Complete Example: Linear Workflow</h2>
        <p>A minimal workflow with start, two steps, and an end. Good template to copy and adapt.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">using Temporalio.Workflows;
using TemporalDashboard.WorkflowDiagramming.Attributes;

[Workflow]
[WorkflowDiagram(Direction = "TD")]
public class SimpleLinearWorkflow
{
    [WorkflowRun]
    [WorkflowStart("Begin")]
    public Task&lt;string&gt; RunAsync() => Task.FromResult("Done");

    [WorkflowStep("Step1", "Process Data", 1)]
    public void ProcessData() { }

    [WorkflowStep("Step2", "Validate Result", 2)]
    public void ValidateResult() { }

    [WorkflowTransition("Start", "Step1")]
    [WorkflowTransition("Step1", "Step2")]
    [WorkflowTransition("Step2", "End")]
    public void Transitions() { }

    [WorkflowEnd("End", "Complete", true)]
    public void End() { }
}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Complete Example: Workflow with Decision</h2>
        <p>Uses a decision node and branches instead of transitions from the decision.</p>
        <pre class="code-block bg-dark text-light p-3 rounded"><code class="language-csharp">[Workflow]
[WorkflowDiagram(Direction = "LR")]
public class DecisionWorkflow
{
    [WorkflowRun]
    [WorkflowStart]
    public Task&lt;string&gt; RunAsync() => Task.FromResult("Done");

    [WorkflowStep("Step1", "Initial Step", 1)]
    public void InitialStep() { }

    [WorkflowDecision("Decision1", "Is Valid?", 2)]
    public void CheckValidity() { }

    [WorkflowBranch("Decision1", "Yes", "Step2")]
    [WorkflowBranch("Decision1", "No", "ErrorEnd", IsFailurePath = true)]
    public void DecisionBranches() { }

    [WorkflowStep("Step2", "Process Valid Data", 3)]
    public void ProcessValid() { }

    [WorkflowTransition("Start", "Step1")]
    [WorkflowTransition("Step1", "Decision1")]
    public void Transitions() { }

    [WorkflowEnd("End", "Success", true)]
    public void SuccessEnd() { }

    [WorkflowEnd("ErrorEnd", "Error", false)]
    public void ErrorEnd() { }
}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Best Practices</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Unique IDs</strong> — Every step needs a unique <code>id</code>; transitions and branches refer to these IDs.</li>
            <li><strong>Order</strong> — Use sequential order numbers (1, 2, 3…) so the diagram layout matches the flow.</li>
            <li><strong>Start</strong> — In transitions, the start node ID must be exactly <code>"Start"</code> (capital S).</li>
            <li><strong>Decisions</strong> — Use <code>[WorkflowBranch]</code> for paths out of a decision; do not use <code>[WorkflowTransition]</code> from decision nodes.</li>
            <li><strong>Labels</strong> — Use clear, business-friendly labels for steps and branches so the diagram is readable for non-developers.</li>
            <li><strong>AI steps</strong> — Set <code>IsAiPowered = true</code> on steps that use AI/ML so they are styled distinctly in the diagram.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
        <h2>Quick Checklist</h2>
        <ul class="list-unstyled">
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>using TemporalDashboard.WorkflowDiagramming.Attributes;</code></li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowDiagram]</code> on the workflow class</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowStart]</code> on the <code>[WorkflowRun]</code> method</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowStep]</code> (or Decision / HumanApproval / End) on each step</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowTransition]</code> for all step-to-step links</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowBranch]</code> for decision outcomes (not Transition)</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ <code>[WorkflowEnd]</code> on completion methods</li>
            <li class="mb-1">☐ Unique IDs and correct <code>"Start"</code> in transitions</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-4">
        <h2>Attribute Reference (Summary)</h2>
        <div class="table-responsive">
            <table class="table table-sm table-bordered">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Attribute</th>
                        <th>Where</th>
                        <th>Purpose</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowDiagram</code></td><td>Class</td><td>Display name, diagram direction</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowStart</code></td><td>Run method</td><td>Start node label</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowStep</code></td><td>Method/class</td><td>Step id, label, order; optional type, AI, success/failure</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowDecision</code></td><td>Method</td><td>Decision id, label, order</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowHumanApproval</code></td><td>Method</td><td>Approval step with description, timeout, role</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowEnd</code></td><td>Method</td><td>End id, label, success/failure</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowTransition</code></td><td>Method</td><td>From step → to step (and optional label)</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>WorkflowBranch</code></td><td>Method</td><td>From decision → target step; use for decisions only</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </section>
</div>

@code {
    protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
    {
        try
        {
            await JSRuntime.InvokeVoidAsync("highlightCode");
        }
        catch { /* Prism may not be loaded yet */ }
    }
}
